The '''Collegium of Black Women Philosophers''' ('''CBWP''') is an organization which was created to increase the visibility of [[black women]] in the field of [[philosophy]] and to allow greater networking and mentoring opportunities for these women. The organization is currently based at [[Pennsylvania State University|Penn State University]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Patel|first=Vimal|date=27 March 2016|title=Diversifying a Discipline|url=http://www.franklin.uga.edu/sites/default/files/Diversifying%20a%20Discipline.pdf|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>
==History== The first meeting of CBWP took place in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://futuristicallyancient.com/2012/10/24/the-my-stery-black-women-who-are-philosophers/|title=The My-Stery: Black Women Who Are Philosophers|last=|first=|date=24 October 2012|website=Aker: Futuristically Ancient|publisher=|access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref> The organization was founded by [[Kathryn Gines]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://feministphilosophers.wordpress.com/2007/10/29/collegium-of-black-women-philosophers/|title=Collegium of Black Women Philosophers|last=|first=|date=29 October 2007|website=Feminist Philosophy|publisher=|access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a9JawU8QRvAC&lpg=PA2&ots=r6S1u8SbLX&dq=%22collegium%20of%20black%20women%20philosophers%22&pg=PA2#v=onepage&q=%22collegium%20of%20black%20women%20philosophers%22&f=false|title=Convergences: Black Feminism and Continental Philosophy|last=Davidson|first=Maria del Guadalupe|last2=Gines|first2=Kathyrn T.|last3=Marcano|first3=Donna-Dale|publisher=State University of New York Press|year=2010|isbn=9781438432670|location=Albany|pages=2|chapter=Introducion|quote=|via=}}</ref> Gines felt that it was important to address the issue of the small number of black women in the field of philosophy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.vanderbilt.edu/2007/01/12/collegium-of-black-women-philosophers-launched-at-vanderbilt-conference-set-for-september-58771/|title=Collegium of Black Women Philosophers launched at Vanderbilt; Conference set for September|last=|first=|date=12 January 2007|work=Vanderbilt News|access-date=25 January 2017|via=}}</ref> Gines reached out black women by [[email]] and was able to contact all thirty-one African American women professors, many of which were able to attend the first conference.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wApVCwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA91&ots=0J5p-zWDue&dq=%22collegium%20of%20black%20women%20philosophers%22&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q=%22collegium%20of%20black%20women%20philosophers%22&f=false|title=Philosophy and the Mixed Race Experience|last=Oshana|first=Marina|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2016|isbn=9781498509428|editor-last=Botts|editor-first=Tina Fernandes|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=80-81|chapter=Through the Looking Glass: What Philosophy Looks LIke From the Inside When You're Not Quite There|quote=|via=}}</ref> The first conference was held at [[Vanderbilt University]] in 2008 and included [[Joyce Mitchell Cook]], the first [[African Americans|African American]] woman to earn a PhD in philosophy.{{Sfn|Romano|2013|p=433}}
