{{Infobox book | name = Revolutionary Suicide | title_orig = | translator = | image = Revolutionary Suicide book cover.jpg | caption = Book cover | author = [[Huey P. Newton]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Black Panther Party]] | genre = [[Autobiography]] | publisher = Random House | pub_date = 1973 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = | isbn = 0-86316-326-2 | oclc = 32406735 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Revolutionary Suicide''''' is an [[autobiography]] written by [[Huey P. Newton]], co-founder and leader of the [[Black Panther Party]] (BPP). The Chief ideologue and strategist of the BPP, Newton taught himself how to read during his last year of high school, which led to his enrollment in [[Merrit College]] in [[Oakland]] in 1966; the same year he formed what was then known as the Black Panther Party for Self-Defense. The Party urged members to challenge the status quo with armed patrols of the impoverished streets of black Oakland, and to form coalitions with other oppressed groups. The party spread across America and internationally as well, forming coalitions with the Vietnamese, Chinese, and Cubans.<ref>Revolutionary Suicide Huey P. Newton, with J. Herman Blake ; introduction by Fredrika Newton. Penguin classics deluxe edition Originally published: New York : Harcourt Brace Jovanovich, 1973.</ref> The book was republished by [[Penguin books]] and includes an introduction by Fredrika Newton (Huey's widow).
